As surface water warms, it tends to form a distinct layer that does not mix well with cooler, nutrient-rich water below, depriving phytoplankton of some of the materials they need to turn CO2 and sunlight into energy. Phytoplankton grows more than a thousand times faster than green plants on land, turning over in 2 to 6 days compared to ~19 years on average for land plants, forests take centuries. However, collapse of vital mineral dust has interrupted and collapsed ocean primary productivity at a rate of 1% per year, this in turn had resulted in damaging feedback mechanisms of ocean warming and acidification which are further accelerating the catastrophic damage to the largest and most potent ecosystem on this blue planet the all important ocean pastures and their phytoplankton. I'm all for re-planting, but we need to stop pushing gigatons of CO2 into the atmosphere, right now. Massive die-off of species could be incredibly fast. Even the "Green New Deal" is probably a drop in the proverbial bucket.

@Randy Hilton Usually when I try that line of discussion I get silence or have my intelligence insulted for not caring enough about the rainforest. In my observation, too many people don't believe that the real issue is a matter of total amount of exposed photosynthesizing plant surfaces and overall plant biomass diverting CO2 from the air. It's amazing to consider a scenario where global flooding from temperature increase would lead to a kind of course-correction where marine plant life would eventually have more room, increase in numbers, reduce the amount of carbon in the air, and potentially return the planet to a slightly lower temperature range again. Imagine how long it would take, though.

@r385671 The threat has been ‚Äúmostly overlooked by climate scientists‚Äù, Petrovskii said, ‚Äúnoting that such a global disaster would come with little notice.‚Äù ‚ÄúA distinct feature of this catastrophe is that there will be few warning signs and little change before it is too late,‚Äù he said. ‚ÄúThat‚Äôs because phytoplankton can continue to produce oxygen and photosynthesize at levels below 6 degrees of temperature rise. Under a 2-degree increase, we will probably see no change; the 4-degree increase would already be dangerously close.‚Äù ‚ÄúAbout two-thirds of the planet‚Äôs total atmospheric oxygen is produced by ocean phytoplankton ‚Äì and therefore cessation would result in the depletion of atmospheric oxygen on a global scale. This would likely result in the mass mortality of animals and humans.‚Äù Those blue deserts, our oceans, cover 72% of this blue planet so this is a very big problem. To put the ocean plant crisis into a terrestrial perspective in each 5 year span over the past 50 years an equivalent amount of ocean green plant life and photosynthesis has been eradicated as if we were to cut down the entire Amazon Rainforest. So add up the deadly toll, in the past 50 years we have eradicated the equivalent to 10 entire Amazon Rainforests! The world is full of alarm and concern about the state of the present day Amazon which has suffered a loss of just 20% of its trees.
@r385671 yes. It's a matter of scale.

@r385671 ¬†It's a matter of scale and density of carbon-based biomass, though. Half-measures add up and growing more plants on a broader scale is something that accrues solid carbon over time. It even can return the carbon to the earth by decaying back into soil that can eventually return to stone. It isn't a "solution" but reducing the topic of carbon emissions to a binary of a total solution or bust would overlook a combination of mitigation that adds up to a solution. Saying that any geographical region is "the Earth's lungs" might be oversimplifying something as intricate as nature.

I intentionally grew trees and a few bushes around my yard at my previous residence, in addition to native Amaranth to eat the leaves and use the seeds as a grain (like my Wixaritari ancestors). Every leafy green surface adds to the overall surface area of plant matter converting CO2. Every branch is a little less CO2 in the air, since that's what the branches are primarily made of. I still grow herbs in my windowsill. I still convince my family and former roommates to use live pine trees for Christmas and I help to transplant them in the spring. Now that I'm temporarily in an apartment, I replaced one of my lightbulbs with a (slightly less effective, but it's power consumption was roughly equivalent to the previous bulb) grow light to supplement the light from the window. The wonderful thing about plants, is that if there's a slight decrease in the global levels of CO2, they'll just grow slower. It doesn't seem like a bad idea to grow more plants as a means of personal contribution to lowering CO2 in the atmosphere. Some plants (like a hanging pot of Creeping Jenny) are fairly hardy and don't require a lot of attention and will bounce right back if you don't water them for over a week (like if you went on a trip and left them inside).
